[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] XLA represents a significant step in optimizing machine learning models, providing developers with tools to enhance computational efficiency and performance.
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] Several machine learning frameworks can use or interoperate with OpenXLA components, including JAX, TensorFlow, and parts of the PyTorch ecosystem.
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] The project is developed with participation from multiple hardware and software organizations that contribute back-end integrations, testing, or specifications for their devices.
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] This includes Alibaba, Amazon Web Services, AMD, Anyscale, Apple, Arm, Cerebras, Google, Graphcore, Hugging Face, Intel, Meta, NVIDIA and SiFive.
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] OpenXLA is developed as a community project with its work carried out in public repositories, discussion forums, and design meetings.
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] Some components, such as StableHLO, began with stewardship from specific organizations and have outlined plans for more formal and distributed governance models as the project matures.
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] The project was announced in 2022 as an effort to coordinate development of ML compiler technologies across major AI companies, notably: Alibaba, Amazon Web Services, AMD, Anyscale, Apple, Arm, Cerebras, Google, Graphcore, Hugging Face, Intel, Meta, NVIDIA and SiFive..
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] It consolidated the XLA compiler, introduced StableHLO as a portable operator set, and created a unified structure for additional tools.
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] Development continues within multiple repositories under the OpenXLA umbrella.
[src:xla-compiler/accelerated-linear-algebra] It was founded by Eugene Burmako, James Rubin, Magnus Hyttsten, Mehdi Amini, Navid Khajouei, and Thea Lamkin from Google's Machine Learning organization.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] It originated as a Fortran library in 1979 and its interface was standardized by the BLAS Technical (BLAST) Forum, whose latest BLAS report can be found on the netlib website.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] This Fortran library is known as the *reference implementation* (sometimes confusingly referred to as *the* BLAS library) and is not optimized for speed but is in the public domain.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Most libraries that offer linear algebra routines conform to the BLAS interface, allowing library users to develop programs that are indifferent to the BLAS library being used.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Many BLAS libraries have been developed, targeting various different hardware platforms.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Examples includes cuBLAS (NVIDIA GPU, GPGPU), rocBLAS (AMD GPU), and OpenBLAS.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Examples of CPU-based BLAS library branches include: OpenBLAS, BLIS (BLAS-like Library Instantiation Software), Arm Performance Libraries, ATLAS, and Intel Math Kernel Library (iMKL).
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] AMD maintains a fork of BLIS that is optimized for the AMD platform.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] ATLAS is a portable library that automatically optimizes itself for an arbitrary architecture. iMKL is a freeware and proprietary vendor library optimized for x86 and x86-64 with a performance emphasis on Intel processors.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] OpenBLAS is an open-source library that is hand-optimized for many of the popular architectures.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The LINPACK benchmarks rely heavily on the BLAS routine `gemm` for its performance measurements.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Many numerical software applications use BLAS-compatible libraries to do linear algebra computations, including LAPACK, LINPACK, Armadillo, GNU Octave, Mathematica, MATLAB, NumPy, R, Julia and Lisp-Stat.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The C++ `std::linalg` library, introduced in C++26, is based on BLAS.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] With the advent of numerical programming, sophisticated subroutine libraries became useful.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] These libraries would contain subroutines for common high-level mathematical operations such as root finding, matrix inversion, and solving systems of equations.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The most prominent numerical programming library was IBM's Scientific Subroutine Package (SSP).
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] These subroutine libraries allowed programmers to concentrate on their specific problems and avoid re-implementing well-known algorithms.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The library routines would also be better than average implementations; matrix algorithms, for example, might use full pivoting to get better numerical accuracy.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The library routines would also have more efficient routines.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] For example, a library may include a program to solve a matrix that is upper triangular.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The libraries would include single-precision and double-precision versions of some algorithms.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Initially, these subroutines used hard-coded loops for their low-level operations.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] For example, if a subroutine needed to perform a matrix multiplication, then the subroutine would have three nested loops.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Linear algebra programs have many common low-level operations (the so-called "kernel" operations, not related to operating systems).
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Between 1973 and 1977, several of these kernel operations were identified.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] These kernel operations became defined subroutines that math libraries could call.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The kernel calls had advantages over hard-coded loops: the library routine would be more readable, there were fewer chances for bugs, and the kernel implementation could be optimized for speed.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] A specification for these kernel operations using scalars and vectors, the level-1 Basic Linear Algebra Subroutines (BLAS), was published in 1979.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] BLAS was used to implement the linear algebra subroutine library LINPACK.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The BLAS abstraction allows customization for high performance.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] For example, LINPACK is a general purpose library that can be used on many different machines without modification.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] LINPACK could use a generic version of BLAS.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] To gain performance, different machines might use tailored versions of BLAS.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] As computer architectures became more sophisticated, vector machines appeared.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] BLAS for a vector machine could use the machine's fast vector operations.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Other machine features became available and could also be exploited.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Consequently, BLAS was augmented from 1984 to 1986 with level-2 kernel operations that concerned vector-matrix operations.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Memory hierarchy was also recognized as something to exploit.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Many computers have cache memory that is much faster than main memory; keeping matrix manipulations localized allows better usage of the cache.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] In 1987 and 1988, the level 3 BLAS were identified to do matrix-matrix operations.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The level 3 BLAS encouraged block-partitioned algorithms.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The original BLAS concerned only densely stored vectors and matrices.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Further extensions to BLAS, such as for sparse matrices, have been addressed.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Modern BLAS implementations typically provide all three levels.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] (called "`axpy`", "a x plus y") and several other operations.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Design of the Level 2 BLAS started in 1984, with results published in 1988.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] where ***A*** and ***B*** can optionally be transposed or hermitian-conjugated inside the routine, and all three matrices may be strided.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] The ordinary matrix multiplication ***A B*** can be performed by setting *α* to one and ***C*** to an all-zeros matrix of the appropriate size.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] where ***T*** is a triangular matrix, among other functionality.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] E.g., by decomposing one or both of ***A***, ***B*** into block matrices, `gemm` can be implemented recursively.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] This is one of the motivations for including the *β* parameter, so the results of previous blocks can be accumulated.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Note that this decomposition requires the special case *β* = 1 which many implementations optimize for, thereby eliminating one multiplication for each value of ***C***.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] This decomposition allows for better locality of reference both in space and time of the data used in the product.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] This, in turn, takes advantage of the cache on the system.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] For systems with more than one level of cache, the blocking can be applied a second time to the order in which the blocks are used in the computation.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Both of these levels of optimization are used in implementations such as ATLAS.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] More recently, implementations by Kazushige Goto have shown that blocking only for the L2 cache, combined with careful amortizing of copying to contiguous memory to reduce TLB misses, is superior to ATLAS.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] A highly tuned implementation based on these ideas is part of the GotoBLAS, OpenBLAS and BLIS.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] BLAS-like Library Instantiation Software framework for rapid instantiation.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] BLIS is a complete refactoring of the GotoBLAS that reduces the amount of code that must be written for a given platform.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] implementation of BLAS for Microsoft's AMP language extension for Visual C++.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Optimized BLAS for Nvidia-based GPU cards, requiring few additional library calls.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Optimized BLAS for Nvidia-based GPU cards, providing only Level 3 functions, but as direct drop-in replacement for other BLAS libraries.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] Multi-platform implementation of many numerical routines.
[src:xla-compiler/basic-linear-algebra-subprograms] It is also possible (and popular) to call the Fortran BLAS from C.
