[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Loop fission attempts to break a loop into multiple loops over the same index range with each new loop taking only a part of the original loop's body.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] to both the data being accessed within the loop and the code in the loop's body.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Another technique that attempts to reduce loop overhead.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] When two adjacent loops would iterate the same number of times regardless of whether that number is known at compile time, their bodies can be combined as long as they do not refer to each other's data.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] conditional, reducing the number of jumps by two, for cases when the loop is executed.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] These optimizations exchange inner loops with outer loops.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] When the loop variables index into an array, such a transformation can improve the locality of reference, depending on the array's layout.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] If a quantity is computed inside a loop during every iteration, and its value is the same for each iteration, it can vastly improve efficiency to hoist it outside the loop and compute its value just once before the loop begins.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] This is particularly important with the address-calculation expressions generated by loops over arrays.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] , because not all code is safe to be hoisted outside the loop.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Some pervasive algorithms such as matrix multiplication have very poor cache behavior and excessive memory accesses.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Loop nest optimization increases the number of cache hits by operating over small blocks and by using a loop interchange.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Loop reversal reverses the order in which values are assigned to the index variable.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Furthermore, on some architectures, loop reversal contributes to smaller code, as when the loop index is being decremented, the condition that needs to be met for the running program to exit the loop is a comparison with zero.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] This is often a special, parameter-less instruction, unlike a comparison with a number, which needs the number to compare to.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Therefore, the amount of bytes needed to store the parameter is saved by using the loop reversal.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Additionally, if the comparison number exceeds the size of word of the platform, in standard loop order, multiple instructions would need to be executed to evaluate the comparison, which is not the case with loop reversal.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Unrolling duplicates the body of the loop multiple times, to decrease the number of times the loop condition is tested and the number of jumps; tests and jumps can hurt performance by impairing the instruction pipeline.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Completely unrolling a loop eliminates all overhead, but requires that the number of iterations be known at compile time.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Loop splitting attempts to simplify a loop or eliminate dependencies by breaking it into multiple loops that have the same bodies but iterate over different contiguous portions of the index range.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] , which can simplify a loop with a problematic first iteration by performing that iteration separately before entering the loop.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Unswitching moves a conditional from inside a loop to outside the loop by duplicating the loop's body inside each of the if and else clauses of the conditional.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] The loop is restructured in such a way that work done in an iteration is split into several parts and done over several iterations.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] In a tight loop, this technique hides the latency between loading and using values.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] A loop is converted into multi-threaded or vectorized (or even both) code to use multiple processors simultaneously in a shared-memory multiprocessor (SMP) machine, including multi-core machines.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Prescient store optimizations allow store operations to occur earlier than would otherwise be permitted in the context of threads and locks.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] The process needs some way of knowing ahead of time what value will be stored by the assignment that it should have followed.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] The purpose of this relaxation is to allow compiler optimization to perform certain kinds of code rearrangements that preserve the semantics of properly synchronized programs.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Data-flow optimizations, based on data-flow analysis, primarily depend on how certain properties of data are propagated by control edges in the control-flow graph.
