[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Interprocedural optimization works on the entire program, across procedure and file boundaries.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] It works tightly with intraprocedural counterparts, carried out with the cooperation of a local part and a global part.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Typical interprocedural optimizations are procedure inlining, interprocedural dead-code elimination, interprocedural constant propagation, and procedure reordering.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] As usual, the compiler needs to perform interprocedural analysis before its actual optimizations.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Interprocedural analyses include alias analysis, array access analysis, and the construction of a call graph.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Interprocedural optimization is common in modern commercial compilers from SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] For a long time, the open source GCC was criticized for a lack of powerful interprocedural analysis and optimizations, though this is now improving.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Another open-source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Due to the extra time and space required by interprocedural analysis, most compilers do not perform it by default.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Users must use compiler options explicitly to tell the compiler to enable interprocedural analysis and other expensive optimizations.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] There can be a wide range of optimizations that a compiler can perform, ranging from simple and straightforward optimizations that take little compilation time to elaborate and complex optimizations that involve considerable amounts of compilation time.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] By the 2000s, it was common for compilers, such as Clang, to have several compiler command options that could affect a variety of optimization choices, starting with the familiar `-O2` switch.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] An approach to isolating optimization is the use of so-called post-pass optimizers (some commercial versions of which date back to mainframe software of the late 1970s).
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] These tools take the executable output by an optimizing compiler and optimize it even further.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Post-pass optimizers usually work on the assembly language or machine code level (in contrast with compilers that optimize intermediate representations of programs).
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] One such example is the Portable C Compiler (PCC) of the 1980s, which had an optional pass that would perform post-optimizations on the generated assembly code.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Another consideration is that optimization algorithms are complicated and, especially when being used to compile large, complex programming languages, can contain bugs that introduce errors in the generated code or cause internal errors during compilation.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Compiler errors of any kind can be disconcerting to the user, but especially so in this case, since it may not be clear that the optimization logic is at fault.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] In the case of internal errors, the problem can be partially ameliorated by a "fail-safe" programming technique in which the optimization logic in the compiler is coded such that a failure is trapped, a warning message issued, and the rest of the compilation proceeds to successful completion.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Early compilers of the 1960s were often primarily concerned with simply compiling code correctly or efficiently, such that compile times were a major concern.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] One notable early optimizing compiler was the IBM FORTRAN H compiler of the late 1960s.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] Another of the earliest and important optimizing compilers, that pioneered several advanced techniques, was that for BLISS (1970), which was described in *The Design of an Optimizing Compiler* (1975).
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] By the late 1980s, optimizing compilers were sufficiently effective that programming in assembly language declined.
[src:xla-compiler/compiler-optimization] This co-evolved with the development of RISC chips and advanced processor features such as superscalar processors, out-of-order execution, and speculative execution, which were designed to be targeted by optimizing compilers rather than by human-written assembly code.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **graph** is an abstract data type that is meant to implement the undirected graph and directed graph concepts from the field of graph theory within mathematics.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure consists of a finite (and possibly mutable) set of *vertices* (also called *nodes* or *points*), together with a set of unordered pairs of these vertices for an undirected graph or a set of ordered pairs for a directed graph.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] These pairs are known as *edges* (also called *links* or *lines*), and for a directed graph are also known as *edges* but also sometimes *arrows* or *arcs*.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertices may be part of the graph structure, or may be external entities represented by integer indices or references.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure may also associate to each edge some *edge value*, such as a symbolic label or a numeric attribute (cost, capacity, length, etc.).
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] This data structure allows the storage of additional data on the vertices.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Additional data can be stored if edges are also stored as objects, in which case each vertex stores its incident edges and each edge stores its incident vertices.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent source vertices and columns represent destination vertices.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Data on edges and vertices must be stored externally.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Only the cost for one edge can be stored between each pair of vertices.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent the vertices and columns represent the edges.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] The entries indicate the incidence relation between the vertex at a row and edge at a column.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] The following table gives the time complexity cost of performing various operations on graphs, for each of these representations, with |*V*| the number of vertices and |*E*| the number of edges.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] In the matrix representations, the entries encode the cost of following an edge.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] The cost of edges that are not present are assumed to be ∞.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] A representation of adjacent vertices via hash tables leads to an amortized average time complexity of $O(1)$ to test adjacency of two given vertices and to remove an edge and an amortized average time complexity of $O(\deg(x))$ to remove a given vertex x of degree $\deg(x)$ .
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] The time complexity of the other operations and the asymptotic space requirement do not change.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] The parallelization of graph problems faces significant challenges: Data-driven computations, unstructured problems, poor locality and high data access to computation ratio.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] The graph representation used for parallel architectures plays a significant role in facing those challenges.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Poorly chosen representations may unnecessarily drive up the communication cost of the algorithm, which will decrease its scalability.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] In the following, shared and distributed memory architectures are considered.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] In the case of a shared memory model, the graph representations used for parallel processing are the same as in the sequential case, since parallel read-only access to the graph representation (e.g. an adjacency list) is efficient in shared memory.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] In the distributed memory model, the usual approach is to partition the vertex set V of the graph into p sets $V_{0},\dots ,V_{p-1}$ .
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Here, p is the amount of available processing elements (PE).
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertex set partitions are then distributed to the PEs with matching index, additionally to the corresponding edges.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Every PE has its own subgraph representation, where edges with an endpoint in another partition require special attention.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] For standard communication interfaces like MPI, the ID of the PE owning the other endpoint has to be identifiable.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] During computation in a distributed graph algorithms, passing information along these edges implies communication.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Partitioning the graph needs to be done carefully - there is a trade-off between low communication and even size partitioning But partitioning a graph is a NP-hard problem, so it is not feasible to calculate them.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Instead, the following heuristics are used.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] 1D partitioning: Every processor gets $n/p$ vertices and the corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be understood as a row-wise or column-wise decomposition of the adjacency matrix.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] For algorithms operating on this representation, this requires an All-to-All communication step as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ message buffer sizes, as each PE potentially has outgoing edges to every other PE.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] 2D partitioning: Every processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Assume the processors are aligned in a rectangle $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ , where $p_{r}$ and $p_{c}$ are the amount of processing elements in each row and column, respectively.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Then each processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix of dimension $(n/p_{r})\times (n/p_{c})$ .
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be visualized as a checkerboard pattern in a matrix.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Therefore, each processing unit can only have outgoing edges to PEs in the same row and column.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] This bounds the amount of communication partners for each PE to $p_{r}+p_{c}-1$ out of $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ possible ones.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Graphs with trillions of edges occur in machine learning, social network analysis, and other areas.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Compressed graph representations have been developed to reduce I/O and memory requirements.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] General techniques such as Huffman coding are applicable, but the adjacency list or adjacency matrix can be processed in specific ways to increase efficiency.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS) are two closely related approaches that are used for exploring all of the nodes in a given connected component.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Both start with an arbitrary node, the "root".
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Strongly connected components can also be found using graph traversals using algorithms such as Kosaraju's algorithm, which is a modified DFS.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] Dijkstra's Algorithm is a Pathfinding Algorithm that can be used on a positively-weighted (meaning all edge weights must be greater than or equal to 0) and/or directed graphs.
[src:xla-compiler/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be used to find the shortest path between two arbitrarily chosen nodes which is commonly applied in routing problems.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:xla-compiler/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] It was developed by the Google Brain team for Google's internal use in research and production.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] The initial version was released under the Apache License 2.0 in 2015.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Google released an updated version, TensorFlow 2.0, in September 2019.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow can be used in a wide variety of programming languages, including Python, JavaScript, C++, and Java, facilitating its use in a range of applications in many sectors.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Starting in 2011, Google Brain built DistBelief as a proprietary machine learning system based on deep learning neural networks.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Its use grew rapidly across diverse Alphabet companies in both research and commercial applications.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Google assigned multiple computer scientists, including Jeff Dean, to simplify and refactor the codebase of DistBelief into a faster, more robust application-grade library, which became TensorFlow.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In 2009, the team, led by Geoffrey Hinton, had implemented generalized backpropagation and other improvements, which allowed generation of neural networks with substantially higher accuracy, for instance a 25% reduction in errors in speech recognition.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow is Google Brain's second-generation system.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Version 1.0.0 was released on February 11, 2017.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] While the reference implementation runs on single devices, TensorFlow can run on multiple CPUs and GPUs (with optional CUDA and SYCL extensions for general-purpose computing on graphics processing units).
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow is available on 64-bit Linux, macOS, Windows, and mobile computing platforms including Android and iOS.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Its flexible architecture allows for easy deployment of computation across a variety of platforms (CPUs, GPUs, TPUs), and from desktops to clusters of servers to mobile and edge devices.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow computations are expressed as stateful dataflow graphs.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] The name TensorFlow derives from the operations that such neural networks perform on multidimensional data arrays, which are referred to as *tensors*.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] During the Google I/O Conference in June 2016, Jeff Dean stated that 1,500 repositories on GitHub mentioned TensorFlow, of which only 5 were from Google.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In March 2018, Google announced TensorFlow.js version 1.0 for machine learning in JavaScript.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In Jan 2019, Google announced TensorFlow 2.0.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] It became officially available in September 2019.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In May 2019, Google announced TensorFlow Graphics for deep learning in computer graphics.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In May 2016, Google announced its Tensor processing unit (TPU), an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC, a hardware chip) built specifically for machine learning and tailored for TensorFlow.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] A TPU is a programmable AI accelerator designed to provide high throughput of low-precision arithmetic (e.g., 8-bit), and oriented toward using or running models rather than training them.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Google announced they had been running TPUs inside their data centers for more than a year, and had found them to deliver an order of magnitude better-optimized performance per watt for machine learning.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In May 2017, Google announced the second-generation, as well as the availability of the TPUs in Google Compute Engine.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] The second-generation TPUs deliver up to 180 teraflops of performance, and when organized into clusters of 64 TPUs, provide up to 11.5 petaflops.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In May 2018, Google announced the third-generation TPUs delivering up to 420 teraflops of performance and 128 GB high bandwidth memory (HBM).
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Cloud TPU v3 Pods offer 100+ petaflops of performance and 32 TB HBM.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In February 2018, Google announced that they were making TPUs available in beta on the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In July 2018, the Edge TPU was announced.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Edge TPU is Google's purpose-built ASIC chip designed to run TensorFlow Lite machine learning (ML) models on small client computing devices such as smartphones known as edge computing.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In May 2017, Google announced TensorFlow Lite as a software stack to support machine learning models for mobile and embedded devices, and in November 2017, provided the developer preview.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In January 2019, the TensorFlow team released a developer preview of the mobile GPU inference engine with OpenGL ES 3.1 Compute Shaders on Android devices and Metal Compute Shaders on iOS devices.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In May 2019, Google announced that their TensorFlow Lite Micro (also known as TensorFlow Lite for Microcontrollers) and ARM's uTensor would be merging.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] As TensorFlow's market share among research papers was declining to the advantage of PyTorch, the TensorFlow Team announced a release of a new major version of the library in September 2019.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow 2.0 introduced many changes, the most significant being TensorFlow eager, which changed the automatic differentiation scheme from the static computational graph to the "Define-by-Run" scheme originally made popular by Chainer and later PyTorch.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Other major changes included removal of old libraries, cross-compatibility between trained models on different versions of TensorFlow, and significant improvements to the performance on GPU.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] AutoDifferentiation is the process of automatically calculating the gradient vector of a model with respect to each of its parameters.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] With this feature, TensorFlow can automatically compute the gradients for the parameters in a model, which is useful to algorithms such as backpropagation which require gradients to optimize performance.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] To do so, the framework must keep track of the order of operations done to the input Tensors in a model, and then compute the gradients with respect to the appropriate parameters.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow includes an "eager execution" mode, which means that operations are evaluated immediately as opposed to being added to a computational graph which is executed later.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Code executed eagerly can be examined step-by step-through a debugger, since data is augmented at each line of code rather than later in a computational graph.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] This execution paradigm is considered to be easier to debug because of its step by step transparency.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In both eager and graph executions, TensorFlow provides an API for distributing computation across multiple devices with various distribution strategies.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] This distributed computing can often speed up the execution of training and evaluating of TensorFlow models and is a common practice in the field of AI.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] To train and assess models, TensorFlow provides a set of loss functions (also known as cost functions).
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Some popular examples include mean squared error (MSE) and binary cross entropy (BCE).
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In order to assess the performance of machine learning models, TensorFlow gives API access to commonly used metrics.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Examples include various accuracy metrics (binary, categorical, sparse categorical) along with other metrics such as Precision, Recall, and Intersection-over-Union (IoU).
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow.nn is a module for executing primitive neural network operations on models.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Some of these operations include variations of convolutions (1/2/3D, Atrous, depthwise), activation functions (Softmax, RELU, GELU, Sigmoid, etc.) and their variations, and other operations (max-pooling, bias-add, etc.).
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow offers a set of optimizers for training neural networks, including ADAM, ADAGRAD, and Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD).
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] When training a model, different optimizers offer different modes of parameter tuning, often affecting a model's convergence and performance.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow serves as a core platform and library for machine learning.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow's APIs use Keras to allow users to make their own machine-learning models.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] In addition to building and training their model, TensorFlow can also help load the data to train the model, and deploy it using TensorFlow Serving.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow provides a stable Python Application Program Interface (API), as well as APIs without backwards compatibility guarantee for JavaScript, C++, and Java.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Third-party language binding packages are also available for C#, Haskell, Julia, MATLAB, Object Pascal, R, Scala, Rust, OCaml, and Crystal.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Bindings that are now archived and unsupported include Go and Swift.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow also has a library for machine learning in JavaScript.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Using the provided JavaScript APIs, TensorFlow.js allows users to use either Tensorflow.js models or converted models from TensorFlow or TFLite, retrain the given models, and run on the web.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] LiteRT, formerly known as TensorFlow Lite, has APIs for mobile apps or embedded devices to generate and deploy TensorFlow models.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] These models are compressed and optimized in order to be more efficient and have a higher performance on smaller capacity devices.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] LiteRT uses FlatBuffers as the data serialization format for network models, eschewing the Protocol Buffers format used by standard TensorFlow models.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TFX) provides numerous components to perform all the operations needed for end-to-end production.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Components include loading, validating, and transforming data, tuning, training, and evaluating the machine learning model, and pushing the model itself into production.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Numpy is one of the most popular Python data libraries, and TensorFlow offers integration and compatibility with its data structures.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Numpy NDarrays, the library's native datatype, are automatically converted to TensorFlow Tensors in TF operations; the same is also true vice versa.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] This allows for the two libraries to work in unison without requiring the user to write explicit data conversions.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Moreover, the integration extends to memory optimization by having TF Tensors share the underlying memory representations of Numpy NDarrays whenever possible.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow also offers a variety of libraries and extensions to advance and extend the models and methods used.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] For example, TensorFlow Recommenders and TensorFlow Graphics are libraries for their respective functional.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Other add-ons, libraries, and frameworks include TensorFlow Model Optimization, TensorFlow Probability, TensorFlow Quantum, and TensorFlow Decision Forests.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Google also released Collaboratory, a TensorFlow Jupyter notebook environment that does not require any setup.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] It runs on Google Cloud and allows users free access to GPUs and the ability to store and share notebooks on Google Drive.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Google JAX is a machine learning framework for transforming numerical functions.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] It is described as bringing together a modified version of autograd (automatic obtaining of the gradient function through differentiation of a function) and TensorFlow's XLA (Accelerated Linear Algebra).
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] It is designed to follow the structure and workflow of NumPy as closely as possible and works with TensorFlow as well as other frameworks such as PyTorch.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] GE Healthcare used TensorFlow to increase the speed and accuracy of MRIs in identifying specific body parts.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Google used TensorFlow to create DermAssist, a free mobile application that allows users to take pictures of their skin and identify potential health complications.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Sinovation Ventures used TensorFlow to identify and classify eye diseases from optical coherence tomography (OCT) scans.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Twitter implemented TensorFlow to rank tweets by importance for a given user, and changed their platform to show tweets in order of this ranking.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Previously, tweets were simply shown in reverse chronological order.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] The photo sharing app VSCO used TensorFlow to help suggest custom filters for photos.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Google officially released RankBrain on October 26, 2015, backed by TensorFlow.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] InSpace, a virtual learning platform, used TensorFlow to filter out toxic chat messages in classrooms.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] Liulishuo, an online English learning platform, utilized TensorFlow to create an adaptive curriculum for each student.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] TensorFlow was used to assess the current abilities of students and also helped decide which content to show based on those capabilities.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] The e-commerce platform Carousell used TensorFlow to provide personalized recommendations for customers.
[src:xla-compiler/tensorflow] The cosmetics company ModiFace used TensorFlow to create an augmented reality experience for customers to test various shades of make-up on their face.
